</B>
				<table border="0" bgcolor="gray" 
				width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr>
				<td style="color: ivory; padding: 4px" colspan="2">
				<span STYLE="font-size: 11pt; font-weight: bold;">&nbsp;&nbsp;Guild Charter</span>
				</td></tr>
				<tr>
					<td align="left" bgcolor="white" style="font-size: 8pt">
					<A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&id=8" style="text-decoration: none; font-size: x-small;">[contents]</A>
					</td>
					<td align="right" bgcolor="white" style="font-size: 8pt">
					<a href="javascript:history.go(-1)" style="text-decoration: none; font-size: x-small;">[back]</a>
					&nbsp;
					<A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&loc=32&id=8" style="text-decoration: none; font-size: x-small;">&lt;&lt;&nbsp;[Miscellany]</A>

					&nbsp;
					<A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&loc=27&id=8" style="text-decoration: none; font-size: x-small;">[Afterword]&nbsp;&gt;&gt;</A>

					</td>
				</tr>
				</table><H3>Unruly Player Guidelines</H3>
Over the course of your career, you will undoubtedly be treated to the honor of meeting those individuals who believe Tunare has gifted them with infinite wisdom, power and grace. They also believe that due to these divine gifts they are better than the rest of us and entitled to a measure of respect and courtesy that they have not earned and will not bestow upon others. Perhaps these people could be controlled if either their parents had given them a better childhood, or if their parents would prevent them from playing this game until after the throes of puberty have passed. Either way they are out there and will make your life interesting at lower levels. People like this rarely survive long enough to trouble you in the high-level game since nobody will help them.<br>
<br>
<b>Verant Policy:</b> Verant GMs are, unfortunately, not very helpful when it comes to mediating player dispute. They usually have no time to help you and will arrive several hours too late to do anything. They will not do anything about a problem until they have witnessed it themselves. You may if you are lucky be able to request a GM or guide's presence as an invisible observer but this is rare. They will always tell you "Camps don't exist, you must share the spawn" for any dispute over loot and camps. You'll find, more often than not, that the troublemaker will call the GMs on you, and don't count on the GM seeing the issue in the same light as you do; sometimes they side with the unruly player because he is playing the situation by the letter of their rules. For kill stealing, GMs will always side with the player who landed the first blow.<br>
<br>
Never, ever attack the other player with crude insults and especially with foul language. They will be quick to report you and the GMs will not side with you if you have done or said anything to make the situation worse.<br>
<br>
<b>Our Policy:</b> Unfortunately, there isn't a whole lot you can do to these people without using their own tactics on them. This will get you and your adversary into the same hot water with the GMs, landing both of you with warnings. There are, however, a few guidelines that you can follow to help you handle these situations.<br>
<br>
1. <b>Verify</b>: Make absolutely sure that whatever happened that is irking you wasn't an accident. It's best to forgive and forget, so if it only happens once (like trains for example) then just let it slide.<br>
<br>
2. <b>Ignore the Troublemaker:</b> This is usually the best policy; if you can ignore them they usually leave and go looking for other people to annoy. In fact, you'll find that avoiding making any inflammatory comments usually is the best way to avoid setting these people off. Verant gave you a /ignore list for a reason. Use it.<br>
<br>
3. <b>Ask the Guild:</b> We've got a few people with psychology backgrounds in our guild, as well as a few players who are so versed in dealing with GMs and bad players that it is laughable. Ask for advice. One of the reasons we started this guild was to make sure we have nobody like this in it.<br>
<br>
4. <b>Appeal to the Troublemaker:</b> Ask this person why they are being such a problem. If they are simply causing trouble due to a lack of knowledge (such as about group waiting lists, for example) then educate them on how things work and try to help them out. Explain why their behavior is wrong and help them understand why.<br>
<br>
5. <b>Report the Troublemaker:</b> The /report playername command sends the last fifteen statements the player made in any chat mode to a logfile the GMs can easily view. If a player makes a statement about training you or swears in chat, wait a few moments (for him to say more) then /report him and /petition a GM. When they arrive you'll be in an excellent position. Be very polite and explain to them what is happening, and ask them to check the report.<br>
<br>
6. <b>Appeal to Others:</b> There are other players in the zone. Chances are your grouped with some of them. Rely on them for support and make sure the GM talks to them about what happened as well.<br>
<br>
7. <b>Leave:</b> Simply leave. There are many places you can level without interference from these people. Ask your guild mates for advice on where to go. If you can't leave (such as from a raid or from a rare camp you are entitled to) then you must go farther and deal with it, or wait for another day.<br>
<br>
8. <b>Keep your Cool:</b> You may find you are sitting at the keyboard shaking with rage. Calm the heck down; it's only a game. Take a few deep breaths and then think of a way to send that rage into the other player.<br>
<br>
9. <b>Flame On:</b> If it reaches this point it's obvious that there's no hope for the individual. You may verbally abuse them, embarrass them, and expose them. NEVER swear even a little in open chat. Remember that everything you say is subject to GM review so never make any incriminating statements, even in guild chat or private tells. It's easy to construct a statement that will cut like a knife into someone's psyche without using any profanity, so think of something that will rankle with them and let it fly. It's best to keep it to personal tells unless you want the whole zone in on it. Verant doesn't like that but if everyone in the zone is flaming them, they'll probably leave. Accusing an incompetent player of having purchased his character on ebay, or accusing a guildless player of having a history of problems are just a few examples, and ones that are almost certainly going to cut deeply. If you find a lot of people sticking up for someone, you may want to back down, you may have misjudged them. Just maybe, you're the problem and not the other player.<br>
<br>
10. <b>Time to Leave:</b> If you're still stuck, get the hell out of there. It's not worth it no matter what the problem was.<br>
<br>
We'd like to be able to tell you, as most others will, that just running out on the situation is the best policy. It isn't. You have to stand up for yourself. If you don't fight back these people will probably continue on, as they always have, just like a typical high-school bully. Be sure to give them a bloody nose for their trouble, even if you get a bit beat up in the process.<br>
<br>
There's no way we can commit the guild to backing people up when these things occur. Sure, we probably will, but please try your hardest to handle it yourself. It's ONLY A GAME. Let things slide. Remember that some people who have a bad day at work come home to take it out on Everquest. You've been there; you know what it's like. Take a few deep breaths. Play an alternate character. Log out and take a walk. Try taking a few days off from Everquest. You'll feel a lot better when you get back.<br>
